  "prompt": "Why was the part B in 70 marks theory of physical education removed by CBSE for the batch 2014-2015 class 12th?",
  "response": "The Central Board of Secondary Education (CBSE) often revises its curriculum and examination patterns to align with the evolving educational standards and to reduce the burden on students. For the batch of 2014-2015, CBSE made significant changes to the Class 12 Physical Education syllabus and examination structure.\n\nOne of the key changes was the removal of Part B, which was worth 70 marks in the theory exam. This decision was part of a broader effort to make the assessment process more balanced and less stressful for students. The rationale behind this change included:\n\n1. **Streamlining the Syllabus**: The removal of Part B aimed to streamline the syllabus, ensuring that students could focus on a more concise set of topics without being overwhelmed by the volume of content.\n\n2. **Reducing Examination Burden**: By removing Part B, the total marks for the theory exam were reduced, which helped in lowering the overall stress and pressure on students.\n\n3. **Focusing on Practical Application**: The revised syllabus placed a greater emphasis on practical skills and application of knowledge, which are crucial in Physical Education. This shift was intended to make the subject more engaging and relevant to students' real-life physical activities and health practices.\n\n4. **Alignment with National Education Policy**: The changes were also in line with the broader objectives of the National Education Policy, which advocates for a more holistic and less exam-centric approach to education.\n\nPost this change, the theory exam for Physical Education in Class 12 was structured in a way that balanced theoretical knowledge with practical skills, ensuring a comprehensive understanding of the subject. The board periodically reviews and updates its curriculum to keep it relevant and effective for students.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
